\chapter{Fuzzy DL OWL 2}
\label{\detokenize{main:fuzzy-dl-owl-2}}\label{\detokenize{main::doc}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
A python porting of the \sphinxhref{https://www.umbertostraccia.it/cs/software/fuzzyDL/fuzzyDL.html}{Fuzzy Description Language} and the \sphinxhref{https://www.umbertostraccia.it/cs/software/FuzzyOWL/index.html}{Fuzzy OWL 2} framework.

\sphinxAtStartPar
A lightweight Python porting of the Fuzzy Description Language (FuzzyDL) and the Fuzzy OWL 2 framework, designed for representing fuzzy logic within description logic and for mapping an knowledge base represented in FuzzyDL to a Fuzzy OWL 2 construct in RDF/XML format.

\sphinxAtStartPar
Features:
\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Object\sphinxhyphen{}oriented representation of Fuzzy Description Logic elements

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Object\sphinxhyphen{}oriented representation of Fuzzy OWL 2 elements

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Mapping from FuzzyDL to Fuzzy OWL 2

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Mapping from Fuzzy OWL 2 to FuzzyDL

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Reasoning in FuzzyDL

\end{itemize}


\section{Directory dl\sphinxhyphen{}examples}
\label{\detokenize{main:directory-dl-examples}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
The directory \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{dl\sphinxhyphen{}examples}} contains a few examples of Knowledge Bases written using the Fuzzy Description Logic language.

\section{Configuration of the MILP solver}
\label{\detokenize{install_and_config:configuration-of-the-milp-solver}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Since version 1.0.1 uses \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{Gurobi Optimizer}} (see \sphinxhref{https://support.gurobi.com/hc/en-us/articles/360044290292-How-do-I-install-Gurobi-for-Python}{gurobipy} for the Fuzzy DL reasoning, please create a GUROBI license to use this library.

\sphinxAtStartPar
For the configuration, create a \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{CONFIG.ini}} file in the same directory used for the execution of the library.
Example of your execution directory:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
your\PYGZus{}directory
├── CONFIG.ini
├── your\PYGZus{}file.py
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
The file \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{CONFIG.ini}} is structured as follows:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
[DEFAULT]
debugPrint = False
epsilon = 0.001
maxIndividuals = \PYGZhy{}1
owlAnnotationLabel = fuzzyLabel
milpProvider = mip
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

The fuzzy number system supports several types of expressions, each with specific mathematical definitions:


\subsection{Basic Fuzzy Number Representation}
\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:basic-fuzzy-number-representation}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{(a, b, c)} represents a fuzzy number with the mathematical definition \((a,b,c)\).


\subsection{Real Number Conversion}
\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:real-number-conversion}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{n} represents a real number that is automatically converted to the fuzzy number \((n,n,n)\).


\subsection{Addition of Fuzzy Numbers}
\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:addition-of-fuzzy-numbers}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
(\(f+\) \(f_1\) \(f_2\) \(\ldots\) \(f_n\)) performs addition of multiple fuzzy numbers, defined mathematically as \((\sum_{i = 0}^{n} a_i, \sum_{i = 0}^{n} b_i, \sum_{i = 0}^{n} c_i)\).


\subsection{Subtraction of Fuzzy Numbers}
\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:subtraction-of-fuzzy-numbers}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
(\(f-\) \(f_1\) \(f_2\)) performs subtraction between two fuzzy numbers, defined mathematically as \((a_1−c_2, b_1 − b_2, c_1 − a_2)\).


\subsection{Product of Fuzzy Numbers}
\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:product-of-fuzzy-numbers}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
(\(f*\) \(f_1\) \(f_2\) \(\ldots\) \(f_n\)) performs multiplication of multiple fuzzy numbers, defined mathematically as \((\prod_{i = 0}^{n} a_i, \prod_{i = 0}^{n} b_i, \prod_{i = 0}^{n} c_i)\).


\subsection{Division of Fuzzy Numbers}
\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:division-of-fuzzy-numbers}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
(\(f/\) \(f_1\) \(f_2\)) performs division between two fuzzy numbers, defined mathematically as \((\frac{a_1}{c_2}, \frac{b_1}{b_2}, \frac{c_1}{a_2})\).

\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:datatype-restriction-operations}}

\sphinxAtStartPar

\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:equality-restrictions-with-variables}}

\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:equality-restrictions-with-fuzzy-numbers}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{\((=\ F\ \text{fuzzy\_number})\)} establishes equality constraints with fuzzy numbers, mathematically expressed as \(\mathrm{sup}_{b^\prime, b \in \Delta_D} [F^\mathcal{I} (x, b) \otimes (b = b^\prime) \otimes {\text{fuzzy\_number}(b^\prime)}^\mathcal{I}]\).

\subsection{Important Constraints and Notes}
\label{\detokenize{new_grammar:important-constraints-and-notes}}

Several constraints apply to the proper use of these concept expressions:
\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\(n_1, \ldots, n_k \in [0, 1]\), with \(\sum_{i=1}^k\ n_i \leq 1\)

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\(w_1, \ldots, w_n \in [0, 1]\), with \(\sum_{i=1}^n\ w_i = 1\)

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\(v_1, \ldots, v_n \in [0, 1]\), with \(\max_{i=1}^n\ v_i = 1\)

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\(y_i\) is the \(i\)\sphinxhyphen{}largest of the \(C_i^\mathcal{I}(x)\)

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\(ow_i\) is the weight \(v_i\) of the \(i\)\sphinxhyphen{}largest of the \(C_i^\mathcal{I}(x)\)

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\(mu_i\) is defined as follows: \(mu_1 = ow_1\), and \(mu_i = ow_i \oplus mu_{i - 1}\) for \(i \in {2, \ldots, n}\)

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
Fuzzy numbers can only appear in existential, universal and datatype restrictions

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar

\sphinxAtStartPar

\end{itemize}

\section{Base Concepts}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:base-concepts}}

\subsection{Concept}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:concept}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Defines a base class of any concept. This is the fundamental class from which all other concept implementations derive.


\subsection{AtomicConcept}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:atomicconcept}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Defines an atomic concept. This represents the smallest, indivisible unit in the fuzzy logic system.


\subsection{TruthConcept}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:truthconcept}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Defines the top \(\top\) and bottom \(\perp\) concepts. These represent absolute truth and absolute falsehood respectively in the logical system.


\section{Logical Operators}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:logical-operators}}

\subsection{OperatorConcept}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:operatorconcept}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
It is the class to handle a logic (Zadeh, Lukasiewicz, and product) connectives (AND, OR, NOT) between fuzzy concepts. This class implements the fundamental logical operations in fuzzy logic systems.


\subsection{AllSomeConcept}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:allsomeconcept}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Defines a universal (\(\forall\)) and existential (\(\exists\)) restrictions on fuzzy concepts. These allow for expressing quantifications in the fuzzy domain.


\subsection{ImpliesConcept}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:impliesconcept}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Defines a zadeh and goedel implies concept. This handles implication operations in fuzzy logic.


\section{Fuzzy Integrals}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:fuzzy-integrals}}

\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:choquetintegral}}
\sphinxAtStartPar

\subsection{SugenoIntegral}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:sugenointegral}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Defines a Sugeno integral of fuzzy concept. This is a particular type of non\sphinxhyphen{}linear integral with respect to fuzzy measures.


\subsection{QsugenoIntegral}
\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:qsugenointegral}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Defines a Quasi\sphinxhyphen{}Sugeno integral of fuzzy concept. This extends the Sugeno integral with additional flexibility.

\label{\detokenize{new_concepts:owaconcept}}
